<!-- doc/src/sgml/extvacuumstatistics.sgml -->

<sect1 id="extvacuumstatistics" xreflabel="ext_vacuum_statistics">
 <title>ext_vacuum_statistics &mdash; extended per-vacuum statistics</title>

 <indexterm zone="extvacuumstatistics">
  <primary>ext_vacuum_statistics</primary>
 </indexterm>

 <para>
  The <filename>ext_vacuum_statistics</filename> module collects detailed
  per-table, per-index, and per-database statistics about every
  <command>VACUUM</command> operation, exposing them through views in the
  <literal>ext_vacuum_statistics</literal> schema. Counters cover buffer I/O
  (read/hit/dirtied/written and timings), WAL volume, page accounting from
  the visibility map, dead-tuple bookkeeping, anti-wraparound failsafe
  invocations, and overall wall-clock / sleep time.
 </para>

 <para>
  Core <productname>PostgreSQL</productname> only emits the
  <function>set_report_vacuum_hook</function> callback inside lazy vacuum;
  this extension installs that callback and is the sole owner of the
  persisted data. It is intentional that the extension does not force
  <quote>collect everything</quote>: both the set of objects to track
  <emphasis>and</emphasis> the categories of metrics to keep can be
  configured at run time, so memory and overhead can be tuned to the actual
  monitoring need.
 </para>

 <sect2 id="extvacuumstatistics-loading">
  <title>Loading the module</title>

  <para>
   The module must be loaded by adding
   <literal>ext_vacuum_statistics</literal> to
   <xref linkend="guc-shared-preload-libraries"/> in
   <filename>postgresql.conf</filename>, because it registers a vacuum hook
   and a custom cumulative-statistics kind at server startup. A server
   restart is required.
  </para>

<programlisting>
shared_preload_libraries = 'ext_vacuum_statistics'
</programlisting>

  <para>
   In each database where the views should be visible:
  </para>

<programlisting>
CREATE EXTENSION ext_vacuum_statistics;
</programlisting>
 </sect2>

 <sect2 id="extvacuumstatistics-config">
  <title>Configuration parameters</title>

  <variablelist>
   <varlistentry>
    <term><varname>vacuum_statistics.enabled</varname> (<type>boolean</type>)</term>
    <listitem>
     <para>
      Master switch. When <literal>off</literal>, the hook returns early and
      no counters are accumulated. Default <literal>on</literal>.
     </para>
    </listitem>
   </varlistentry>

   <varlistentry>
    <term><varname>vacuum_statistics.object_types</varname> (<type>string</type>)</term>
    <listitem>
     <para>
      Selects which object kinds receive entries:
      <literal>all</literal> (databases plus relations &mdash; the default),
      <literal>databases</literal> (per-database aggregates only), or
      <literal>relations</literal> (per-table and per-index entries; no
      database-level aggregate).
     </para>
    </listitem>
   </varlistentry>

   <varlistentry>
    <term><varname>vacuum_statistics.track_relations</varname> (<type>string</type>)</term>
    <listitem>
     <para>
      When relations are tracked, narrow the set further:
      <literal>all</literal> (default), <literal>system</literal>
      (only catalogs &mdash; <function>IsCatalogRelationOid()</function>
      returns true), or <literal>user</literal> (everything else). Has no
      effect when <varname>object_types</varname> is
      <literal>databases</literal>.
     </para>
    </listitem>
   </varlistentry>

   <varlistentry>
    <term><varname>vacuum_statistics.track_databases_from_list</varname> (<type>boolean</type>)</term>
    <listitem>
     <para>
      When <literal>on</literal>, track only databases whose OID was
      registered via <function>add_track_database()</function>. Default
      <literal>off</literal> (governed by
      <varname>object_types</varname>).
     </para>
    </listitem>
   </varlistentry>

   <varlistentry>
    <term><varname>vacuum_statistics.track_relations_from_list</varname> (<type>boolean</type>)</term>
    <listitem>
     <para>
      When <literal>on</literal>, track only relations whose
      <literal>(dboid, reloid)</literal> pair was registered via
      <function>add_track_relation()</function>; <literal>dboid = 0</literal>
      is a wildcard that matches the relation in any database. Default
      <literal>off</literal>.
     </para>
    </listitem>
   </varlistentry>

   <varlistentry>
    <term><varname>vacuum_statistics.collect</varname> (<type>string</type>)</term>
    <listitem>
     <para>
      Comma- or whitespace-separated list of metric categories to
      accumulate: <literal>buffers</literal>, <literal>wal</literal>,
      <literal>general</literal>, <literal>timing</literal>, or
      <literal>all</literal> (the default). Categories not listed are
      skipped on the hook side and never reach shared memory, which keeps
      the cost of the handler lower when only a slice of the metrics is
      interesting.
     </para>
    </listitem>
   </varlistentry>
  </variablelist>

  <para>
   All parameters have <literal>SUSET</literal> context: superusers may
   change them per-session, or globally via
   <command>ALTER SYSTEM</command> / <filename>postgresql.conf</filename>.
   None of them require a restart.
  </para>
 </sect2>

 <sect2 id="extvacuumstatistics-filtering">
  <title>Filtering: which objects get tracked</title>

  <para>
   This is where the main flexibility lives &mdash; the extension does not
   force <quote>collect everything</quote>, but lets you choose both
   <emphasis>what</emphasis> to track and <emphasis>which metrics</emphasis>
   to keep. Three filters are evaluated in order; an entry must pass all
   three.
  </para>

  <sect3 id="extvacuumstatistics-filter-object">
   <title>By object type</title>

   <para>
    You can limit collection to databases only (without per-table detail),
    to relations only, or collect both (the default). Among relations, you
    can additionally filter <literal>system</literal> /
    <literal>user</literal> / <literal>all</literal>. The relation filter
    applies uniformly to tables and their indexes &mdash; the two cannot
    be filtered independently.
   </para>

<programlisting>
-- per-database aggregates only (smallest footprint)
SET vacuum_statistics.object_types = 'databases';

-- only user tables and their indexes
SET vacuum_statistics.object_types = 'relations';
SET vacuum_statistics.track_relations = 'user';

-- only system catalogs
SET vacuum_statistics.track_relations = 'system';
</programlisting>
  </sect3>

  <sect3 id="extvacuumstatistics-filter-list">
   <title>By an explicit list</title>

   <para>
    An alternative to <quote>by type</quote> is a whitelist: turn the
    corresponding mode on, and the extension starts collecting statistics
    only for the databases and tables that were explicitly registered via
    <function>add_track_database()</function> /
    <function>add_track_relation()</function> (with matching
    <function>remove_track_*</function> for removal). When the lists are
    off, the type filter is in effect; when they are on, only the list
    applies. This is convenient when you are interested in monitoring
    specific <quote>hot</quote> tables and do not want to spend memory on
    statistics for everything else.
   </para>

   <para>
    The list is persisted to disk as
    <filename>pg_stat/ext_vacuum_statistics_track.oid</filename>, so the
    selection survives restart. Concurrency is handled carefully:
    <function>add_track_*</function> may be called from multiple sessions,
    plus an <symbol>object_access_hook</symbol> cleans an entry on
    <command>DROP</command>. To avoid a torn file, access to the list is
    serialized via a dedicated <literal>LWLock</literal> tranche
    (requested from a <symbol>shmem_request_hook</symbol>), and the file
    itself is written atomically &mdash; first to a temporary file, then
    <function>fflush</function> + <function>pg_fsync</function> +
    <function>durable_rename</function>. All I/O return codes are checked;
    on error the temporary file is removed and the real one is left
    untouched, and a <literal>PG_TRY</literal>/<literal>PG_CATCH</literal>
    pair guarantees cleanup if <function>ereport(ERROR)</function> fires
    mid-write. Reads take the same lock in shared mode so a concurrent
    write cannot tear the load.
   </para>

<programlisting>
-- enable list-based filtering
SET vacuum_statistics.track_databases_from_list = on;
SET vacuum_statistics.track_relations_from_list = on;

-- pick what we care about
SELECT ext_vacuum_statistics.add_track_database(
    (SELECT oid FROM pg_database WHERE datname = current_database()));
SELECT ext_vacuum_statistics.add_track_relation(
    (SELECT oid FROM pg_database WHERE datname = current_database()),
    'public.mytable'::regclass);

-- inspect
SELECT * FROM ext_vacuum_statistics.track_list();

-- remove
SELECT ext_vacuum_statistics.remove_track_relation(0, 'public.mytable'::regclass);
SELECT ext_vacuum_statistics.remove_track_database(
    (SELECT oid FROM pg_database WHERE datname = current_database()));
</programlisting>

   <para>
    Passing <literal>0</literal> for <parameter>dboid</parameter> in
    <function>add_track_relation()</function> registers the relation for
    <emphasis>any</emphasis> database with that OID.
   </para>
  </sect3>

  <sect3 id="extvacuumstatistics-filter-metric">
   <title>By metric category</title>

   <para>
    Orthogonal to the object filters,
    <varname>vacuum_statistics.collect</varname> takes a list and turns on
    the categories of interest &mdash; buffers, WAL, general counters, or
    timings (or <literal>all</literal>). Unwanted categories are simply
    skipped on the hook handler side and never make it into the
    <literal>pgstat</literal> entry, which reduces the overhead of the
    handler itself. This is useful when, for example, only timings are
    needed: in that case the extension does not waste cycles copying the
    buffer and WAL fields.
   </para>

<programlisting>
-- only WAL and timing counters; skip buffer/general bookkeeping
SET vacuum_statistics.collect = 'wal, timing';
</programlisting>
  </sect3>
 </sect2>

 <sect2 id="extvacuumstatistics-functions">
  <title>Functions</title>

  <variablelist>
   <varlistentry>
    <term>
     <function>ext_vacuum_statistics.add_track_database(dboid <type>oid</type>)</function>
     <returnvalue>void</returnvalue>
    </term>
    <listitem>
     <para>
      Append <parameter>dboid</parameter> to the database whitelist
      persisted in
      <filename>pg_stat/ext_vacuum_statistics_track.oid</filename>. Has no
      effect on its own &mdash; arm the filter with
      <varname>vacuum_statistics.track_databases_from_list = on</varname>.
     </para>
    </listitem>
   </varlistentry>

   <varlistentry>
    <term>
     <function>ext_vacuum_statistics.remove_track_database(dboid <type>oid</type>)</function>
     <returnvalue>void</returnvalue>
    </term>
    <listitem>
     <para>
      Remove a previously added database from the whitelist. Idempotent
      &mdash; absent OIDs are silently ignored.
     </para>
    </listitem>
   </varlistentry>

   <varlistentry>
    <term>
     <function>ext_vacuum_statistics.add_track_relation(dboid <type>oid</type>, reloid <type>oid</type>)</function>
     <returnvalue>void</returnvalue>
    </term>
    <listitem>
     <para>
      Append <literal>(dboid, reloid)</literal> to the relation whitelist.
      <literal>dboid = 0</literal> is a wildcard matching any database.
     </para>
    </listitem>
   </varlistentry>

   <varlistentry>
    <term>
     <function>ext_vacuum_statistics.remove_track_relation(dboid <type>oid</type>, reloid <type>oid</type>)</function>
     <returnvalue>void</returnvalue>
    </term>
    <listitem>
     <para>
      Remove a previously added relation from the whitelist. The
      <symbol>object_access_hook</symbol> also removes entries
      automatically when the relation is dropped.
     </para>
    </listitem>
   </varlistentry>

   <varlistentry>
    <term>
     <function>ext_vacuum_statistics.track_list()</function>
     <returnvalue>setof record</returnvalue> (<literal>track_kind text, dboid oid, reloid oid</literal>)
    </term>
    <listitem>
     <para>
      Return the current whitelist contents. <literal>track_kind</literal>
      is <literal>database</literal> or <literal>relation</literal>;
      <literal>dboid</literal> or <literal>reloid</literal> may be NULL for
      cluster-wide entries.
     </para>
    </listitem>
   </varlistentry>

   <varlistentry>
    <term>
     <function>ext_vacuum_statistics.vacuum_statistics_reset()</function>
     <returnvalue>void</returnvalue>
    </term>
    <listitem>
     <para>
      Reset every counter in both the per-relation and per-database
      cumulative-stats kinds owned by the extension. The whitelist
      <emphasis>is not</emphasis> touched by this call.
     </para>
    </listitem>
   </varlistentry>

   <varlistentry>
    <term>
     <function>ext_vacuum_statistics.shared_memory_size()</function>
     <returnvalue>bigint</returnvalue>
    </term>
    <listitem>
     <para>
      Return the total amount of shared memory (in bytes) currently used
      by entries the extension manages. Useful for capacity planning.
     </para>
    </listitem>
   </varlistentry>
  </variablelist>
 </sect2>

 <sect2 id="extvacuumstatistics-privileges">
  <title>Privileges</title>

  <para>
   The whitelist mutators &mdash;
   <function>add_track_database()</function>,
   <function>remove_track_database()</function>,
   <function>add_track_relation()</function>,
   <function>remove_track_relation()</function> &mdash; require either
   superuser, or membership in the
   <literal>pg_read_all_stats</literal> role. At the SQL level
   <literal>EXECUTE</literal> is revoked from
   <literal>PUBLIC</literal> and granted only to
   <literal>pg_read_all_stats</literal>, so a regular user has no path to
   mutate the list. Reading the views and calling
   <function>track_list()</function> /
   <function>shared_memory_size()</function> /
   <function>vacuum_statistics_reset()</function> follow standard
   <productname>PostgreSQL</productname> permissions, like the regular
   statistics views.
  </para>
 </sect2>

 <sect2 id="extvacuumstatistics-view-database">
  <title>The <structname>pg_stats_vacuum_database</structname> view</title>

  <indexterm zone="extvacuumstatistics-view-database">
   <primary>pg_stats_vacuum_database</primary>
  </indexterm>

  <para>
   The view <structname>pg_stats_vacuum_database</structname> contains one
   row for each database in the cluster for which at least one vacuum has
   completed since the extension was loaded (or the counters were reset).
   Columns aggregate the per-table and per-index numbers; reltype-specific
   counters (<structfield>pages_*</structfield>, <structfield>tuples_*</structfield>)
   are not summed at the database level.
  </para>

  <table>
   <title><structname>pg_stats_vacuum_database</structname> Columns</title>
   <tgroup cols="1">
    <thead>
     <row>
      <entry role="catalog_table_entry"><para role="column_definition">
       Column Type
      </para>
      <para>
       Description
      </para></entry>
     </row>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
     <row>
      <entry role="catalog_table_entry"><para role="column_definition">
       <structfield>dbid</structfield> <type>oid</type>
      </para>
      <para>OID of the database</para></entry>
     </row>
     <row>
      <entry role="catalog_table_entry"><para role="column_definition">
       <structfield>total_blks_read</structfield> <type>int8</type>
      </para>
      <para>Number of database blocks read by vacuum operations performed on this database</para></entry>
     </row>
     <row>
      <entry role="catalog_table_entry"><para role="column_definition">
       <structfield>total_blks_hit</structfield> <type>int8</type>
      </para>
      <para>Number of times database blocks were found in the buffer cache by vacuum operations performed on this database</para></entry>
     </row>
     <row>
      <entry role="catalog_table_entry"><para role="column_definition">
       <structfield>total_blks_dirtied</structfield> <type>int8</type>
      </para>
      <para>Number of database blocks dirtied by vacuum operations performed on this database</para></entry>
     </row>
     <row>
      <entry role="catalog_table_entry"><para role="column_definition">
       <structfield>total_blks_written</structfield> <type>int8</type>
      </para>
      <para>Number of database blocks written by vacuum operations performed on this database</para></entry>
     </row>
     <row>
      <entry role="catalog_table_entry"><para role="column_definition">
       <structfield>wal_records</structfield> <type>int8</type>
      </para>
      <para>Total number of WAL records generated by vacuum operations performed on this database</para></entry>
     </row>
     <row>
      <entry role="catalog_table_entry"><para role="column_definition">
       <structfield>wal_fpi</structfield> <type>int8</type>
      </para>
      <para>Total number of WAL full page images generated by vacuum operations performed on this database</para></entry>
     </row>
     <row>
      <entry role="catalog_table_entry"><para role="column_definition">
       <structfield>wal_bytes</structfield> <type>numeric</type>
      </para>
      <para>Total amount of WAL bytes generated by vacuum operations performed on this database</para></entry>
     </row>
     <row>
      <entry role="catalog_table_entry"><para role="column_definition">
       <structfield>blk_read_time</structfield> <type>float8</type>
      </para>
      <para>Time spent reading database blocks by vacuum operations performed on this database, in milliseconds (only when <xref linkend="guc-track-io-timing"/> is enabled, otherwise zero)</para></entry>
     </row>
     <row>
      <entry role="catalog_table_entry"><para role="column_definition">
       <structfield>blk_write_time</structfield> <type>float8</type>
      </para>
      <para>Time spent writing database blocks by vacuum operations performed on this database, in milliseconds (only when <xref linkend="guc-track-io-timing"/> is enabled, otherwise zero)</para></entry>
     </row>
     <row>
      <entry role="catalog_table_entry"><para role="column_definition">
       <structfield>delay_time</structfield> <type>float8</type>
      </para>
      <para>Time spent sleeping in a vacuum delay point, in milliseconds (see <xref linkend="runtime-config-resource-vacuum-cost"/>)</para></entry>
     </row>
     <row>
      <entry role="catalog_table_entry"><para role="column_definition">
       <structfield>total_time</structfield> <type>float8</type>
      </para>
      <para>Total wall-clock time of vacuuming relations in this database, in milliseconds. Includes idle time spent in I/O and lock waits.</para></entry>
     </row>
     <row>
      <entry role="catalog_table_entry"><para role="column_definition">
       <structfield>wraparound_failsafe_count</structfield> <type>int4</type>
      </para>
      <para>Number of urgent anti-wraparound vacuum cycles triggered while vacuuming relations in this database</para></entry>
     </row>
     <row>
      <entry role="catalog_table_entry"><para role="column_definition">
       <structfield>errors</structfield> <type>int4</type>
      </para>
      <para>Number of vacuum operations on this database that ended with an error</para></entry>
     </row>
    </tbody>
   </tgroup>
  </table>
 </sect2>

 <sect2 id="extvacuumstatistics-view-tables">
  <title>The <structname>pg_stats_vacuum_tables</structname> view</title>

  <indexterm zone="extvacuumstatistics-view-tables">
   <primary>pg_stats_vacuum_tables</primary>
  </indexterm>

  <para>
   The view <structname>pg_stats_vacuum_tables</structname> contains one
   row for each table in the current database (including TOAST tables)
   that has been vacuumed since the extension was loaded. Buffer/WAL/time
   columns include work done while vacuuming this table's indexes;
   reltype-specific table counters (pages and tuple counters below) cover
   the heap only.
  </para>

  <table>
   <title><structname>pg_stats_vacuum_tables</structname> Columns</title>
   <tgroup cols="1">
    <thead>
     <row>
      <entry role="catalog_table_entry"><para role="column_definition">
       Column Type
      </para>
      <para>
       Description
      </para></entry>
     </row>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
     <row>
      <entry role="catalog_table_entry"><para role="column_definition">
       <structfield>relid</structfield> <type>oid</type>
      </para>
      <para>OID of the table</para></entry>
     </row>
     <row>
      <entry role="catalog_table_entry"><para role="column_definition">
       <structfield>schemaname</structfield> <type>name</type>
      </para>
      <para>Name of the schema this table is in</para></entry>
     </row>
     <row>
      <entry role="catalog_table_entry"><para role="column_definition">
       <structfield>relname</structfield> <type>name</type>
      </para>
      <para>Name of this table</para></entry>
     </row>
     <row>
      <entry role="catalog_table_entry"><para role="column_definition">
       <structfield>total_blks_read</structfield> <type>int8</type>
      </para>
      <para>Number of database blocks read by vacuum operations performed on this table (heap + indexes)</para></entry>
     </row>
     <row>
      <entry role="catalog_table_entry"><para role="column_definition">
       <structfield>total_blks_hit</structfield> <type>int8</type>
      </para>
      <para>Number of times database blocks were found in the buffer cache by vacuum operations performed on this table (heap + indexes)</para></entry>
     </row>
     <row>
      <entry role="catalog_table_entry"><para role="column_definition">
       <structfield>total_blks_dirtied</structfield> <type>int8</type>
      </para>
      <para>Number of database blocks dirtied by vacuum operations on this table</para></entry>
     </row>
     <row>
      <entry role="catalog_table_entry"><para role="column_definition">
       <structfield>total_blks_written</structfield> <type>int8</type>
      </para>
      <para>Number of database blocks written by vacuum operations on this table</para></entry>
     </row>
     <row>
      <entry role="catalog_table_entry"><para role="column_definition">
       <structfield>rel_blks_read</structfield> <type>int8</type>
      </para>
      <para>Number of blocks vacuum operations read directly from this table's relation files</para></entry>
     </row>
     <row>
      <entry role="catalog_table_entry"><para role="column_definition">
       <structfield>rel_blks_hit</structfield> <type>int8</type>
      </para>
      <para>Number of times blocks of this table were already in the buffer cache when vacuum needed them (so no read was issued)</para></entry>
     </row>
     <row>
      <entry role="catalog_table_entry"><para role="column_definition">
       <structfield>pages_scanned</structfield> <type>int8</type>
      </para>
      <para>Number of heap pages examined by vacuum (i.e., not skipped via the visibility map)</para></entry>
     </row>
     <row>
      <entry role="catalog_table_entry"><para role="column_definition">
       <structfield>pages_removed</structfield> <type>int8</type>
      </para>
      <para>Number of heap pages physically removed by vacuum truncation (relation storage shrink)</para></entry>
     </row>
     <row>
      <entry role="catalog_table_entry"><para role="column_definition">
       <structfield>vm_new_frozen_pages</structfield> <type>int8</type>
      </para>
      <para>Number of pages newly marked all-frozen in the visibility map by vacuum</para></entry>
     </row>
     <row>
      <entry role="catalog_table_entry"><para role="column_definition">
       <structfield>vm_new_visible_pages</structfield> <type>int8</type>
      </para>
      <para>Number of pages newly marked all-visible in the visibility map by vacuum (without all-frozen)</para></entry>
     </row>
     <row>
      <entry role="catalog_table_entry"><para role="column_definition">
       <structfield>vm_new_visible_frozen_pages</structfield> <type>int8</type>
      </para>
      <para>Number of pages newly marked all-visible <emphasis>and</emphasis> all-frozen in one step</para></entry>
     </row>
     <row>
      <entry role="catalog_table_entry"><para role="column_definition">
       <structfield>tuples_deleted</structfield> <type>int8</type>
      </para>
      <para>Number of dead tuples vacuum removed from this table</para></entry>
     </row>
     <row>
      <entry role="catalog_table_entry"><para role="column_definition">
       <structfield>tuples_frozen</structfield> <type>int8</type>
      </para>
      <para>Number of tuples vacuum marked frozen</para></entry>
     </row>
     <row>
      <entry role="catalog_table_entry"><para role="column_definition">
       <structfield>recently_dead_tuples</structfield> <type>int8</type>
      </para>
      <para>Dead tuples vacuum left in place because they are still visible to some open transaction</para></entry>
     </row>
     <row>
      <entry role="catalog_table_entry"><para role="column_definition">
       <structfield>missed_dead_tuples</structfield> <type>int8</type>
      </para>
      <para>Fully DEAD tuples that vacuum could not prune due to a failure to acquire a cleanup lock on the heap page</para></entry>
     </row>
     <row>
      <entry role="catalog_table_entry"><para role="column_definition">
       <structfield>missed_dead_pages</structfield> <type>int8</type>
      </para>
      <para>Number of pages that contained at least one <structfield>missed_dead_tuples</structfield></para></entry>
     </row>
     <row>
      <entry role="catalog_table_entry"><para role="column_definition">
       <structfield>index_vacuum_count</structfield> <type>int8</type>
      </para>
      <para>Number of times indexes on this table were processed during the vacuum</para></entry>
     </row>
     <row>
      <entry role="catalog_table_entry"><para role="column_definition">
       <structfield>wraparound_failsafe_count</structfield> <type>int4</type>
      </para>
      <para>Number of urgent anti-wraparound vacuum cycles triggered for this table</para></entry>
     </row>
     <row>
      <entry role="catalog_table_entry"><para role="column_definition">
       <structfield>wal_records</structfield> <type>int8</type>
      </para>
      <para>Total number of WAL records generated by vacuum operations on this table</para></entry>
     </row>
     <row>
      <entry role="catalog_table_entry"><para role="column_definition">
       <structfield>wal_fpi</structfield> <type>int8</type>
      </para>
      <para>Total number of WAL full page images generated by vacuum operations on this table</para></entry>
     </row>
     <row>
      <entry role="catalog_table_entry"><para role="column_definition">
       <structfield>wal_bytes</structfield> <type>numeric</type>
      </para>
      <para>Total amount of WAL bytes generated by vacuum operations on this table</para></entry>
     </row>
     <row>
      <entry role="catalog_table_entry"><para role="column_definition">
       <structfield>blk_read_time</structfield> <type>float8</type>
      </para>
      <para>Time spent reading database blocks by vacuum operations on this table, in milliseconds (only when <xref linkend="guc-track-io-timing"/> is enabled)</para></entry>
     </row>
     <row>
      <entry role="catalog_table_entry"><para role="column_definition">
       <structfield>blk_write_time</structfield> <type>float8</type>
      </para>
      <para>Time spent writing database blocks by vacuum operations on this table, in milliseconds (only when <xref linkend="guc-track-io-timing"/> is enabled)</para></entry>
     </row>
     <row>
      <entry role="catalog_table_entry"><para role="column_definition">
       <structfield>delay_time</structfield> <type>float8</type>
      </para>
      <para>Time spent sleeping in a vacuum delay point while vacuuming this table, in milliseconds</para></entry>
     </row>
     <row>
      <entry role="catalog_table_entry"><para role="column_definition">
       <structfield>total_time</structfield> <type>float8</type>
      </para>
      <para>Total wall-clock time spent vacuuming this table (heap + indexes + waits), in milliseconds</para></entry>
     </row>
    </tbody>
   </tgroup>
  </table>
 </sect2>

 <sect2 id="extvacuumstatistics-view-indexes">
  <title>The <structname>pg_stats_vacuum_indexes</structname> view</title>

  <indexterm zone="extvacuumstatistics-view-indexes">
   <primary>pg_stats_vacuum_indexes</primary>
  </indexterm>

  <para>
   The view <structname>pg_stats_vacuum_indexes</structname> contains one
   row per index that has been touched by vacuum since the extension was
   loaded (TOAST indexes included). Buffer/WAL/time counters cover only
   the index work itself, not the parent heap.
  </para>

  <table>
   <title><structname>pg_stats_vacuum_indexes</structname> Columns</title>
   <tgroup cols="1">
    <thead>
     <row>
      <entry role="catalog_table_entry"><para role="column_definition">
       Column Type
      </para>
      <para>
       Description
      </para></entry>
     </row>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
     <row>
      <entry role="catalog_table_entry"><para role="column_definition">
       <structfield>relid</structfield> <type>oid</type>
      </para>
      <para>OID of the index</para></entry>
     </row>
     <row>
      <entry role="catalog_table_entry"><para role="column_definition">
       <structfield>schemaname</structfield> <type>name</type>
      </para>
      <para>Name of the schema this index is in</para></entry>
     </row>
     <row>
      <entry role="catalog_table_entry"><para role="column_definition">
       <structfield>relname</structfield> <type>name</type>
      </para>
      <para>Name of this index</para></entry>
     </row>
     <row>
      <entry role="catalog_table_entry"><para role="column_definition">
       <structfield>total_blks_read</structfield> <type>int8</type>
      </para>
      <para>Number of database blocks read by vacuum operations on this index</para></entry>
     </row>
     <row>
      <entry role="catalog_table_entry"><para role="column_definition">
       <structfield>total_blks_hit</structfield> <type>int8</type>
      </para>
      <para>Number of times database blocks were found in the buffer cache by vacuum operations on this index</para></entry>
     </row>
     <row>
      <entry role="catalog_table_entry"><para role="column_definition">
       <structfield>total_blks_dirtied</structfield> <type>int8</type>
      </para>
      <para>Number of database blocks dirtied by vacuum operations on this index</para></entry>
     </row>
     <row>
      <entry role="catalog_table_entry"><para role="column_definition">
       <structfield>total_blks_written</structfield> <type>int8</type>
      </para>
      <para>Number of database blocks written by vacuum operations on this index</para></entry>
     </row>
     <row>
      <entry role="catalog_table_entry"><para role="column_definition">
       <structfield>rel_blks_read</structfield> <type>int8</type>
      </para>
      <para>Number of blocks vacuum operations read directly from this index's relation files</para></entry>
     </row>
     <row>
      <entry role="catalog_table_entry"><para role="column_definition">
       <structfield>rel_blks_hit</structfield> <type>int8</type>
      </para>
      <para>Number of times blocks of this index were already in the buffer cache when vacuum needed them</para></entry>
     </row>
     <row>
      <entry role="catalog_table_entry"><para role="column_definition">
       <structfield>pages_deleted</structfield> <type>int8</type>
      </para>
      <para>Number of pages marked deleted by vacuum (free space within the index file; the file size may not change)</para></entry>
     </row>
     <row>
      <entry role="catalog_table_entry"><para role="column_definition">
       <structfield>tuples_deleted</structfield> <type>int8</type>
      </para>
      <para>Number of dead tuples vacuum removed from this index</para></entry>
     </row>
     <row>
      <entry role="catalog_table_entry"><para role="column_definition">
       <structfield>wal_records</structfield> <type>int8</type>
      </para>
      <para>Total number of WAL records generated by vacuum operations on this index</para></entry>
     </row>
     <row>
      <entry role="catalog_table_entry"><para role="column_definition">
       <structfield>wal_fpi</structfield> <type>int8</type>
      </para>
      <para>Total number of WAL full page images generated by vacuum operations on this index</para></entry>
     </row>
     <row>
      <entry role="catalog_table_entry"><para role="column_definition">
       <structfield>wal_bytes</structfield> <type>numeric</type>
      </para>
      <para>Total amount of WAL bytes generated by vacuum operations on this index</para></entry>
     </row>
     <row>
      <entry role="catalog_table_entry"><para role="column_definition">
       <structfield>blk_read_time</structfield> <type>float8</type>
      </para>
      <para>Time spent reading database blocks by vacuum operations on this index, in milliseconds (only when <xref linkend="guc-track-io-timing"/> is enabled)</para></entry>
     </row>
     <row>
      <entry role="catalog_table_entry"><para role="column_definition">
       <structfield>blk_write_time</structfield> <type>float8</type>
      </para>
      <para>Time spent writing database blocks by vacuum operations on this index, in milliseconds (only when <xref linkend="guc-track-io-timing"/> is enabled)</para></entry>
     </row>
     <row>
      <entry role="catalog_table_entry"><para role="column_definition">
       <structfield>delay_time</structfield> <type>float8</type>
      </para>
      <para>Time spent sleeping in a vacuum delay point while vacuuming this index, in milliseconds</para></entry>
     </row>
     <row>
      <entry role="catalog_table_entry"><para role="column_definition">
       <structfield>total_time</structfield> <type>float8</type>
      </para>
      <para>Total wall-clock time spent vacuuming this index, in milliseconds</para></entry>
     </row>
    </tbody>
   </tgroup>
  </table>
 </sect2>

 <sect2 id="extvacuumstatistics-author">
  <title>Author</title>
  <para>
   Alena Rybakina, Andrei Lepikhov, Andrei Zubkov.
  </para>
 </sect2>

</sect1>
